de.tuhh.diss.harborstorage.sim

Class PhysicalCrane

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.tuhh.diss.harborstorage.sim.PhysicalCrane

  • public class PhysicalCrane
extends java.lang.Object
    This class mimics a crane of a "real" automatic storage and retrieve system. The motor of its storage/retrieval crane can be moved along x (horizontal) and y (vertical) axes into position in front of a storage slot, where it can put packets or retrieve packets stored earlier.

    IMPORTANT NOTE: Keep in mind that the motor does not necessarily stays in the same position (although it will do so in nearly all cases) between calling one of the getPosition methods and calling the stop method. You should check whether the motor is really in the right position before trying to retrieve or store a storage element.

    Author:
    Weigel

    • Method Detail

      • loadElement

        public void loadElement(StorageElement e)
        Loads a new StorageElement to the crane. For this, the crane has to be in its loading position. Also prints out some information about the loading operation to the console. The format for this is information is

        "(crane --\gt; packet_ID|size:WxHxD|Description)"

        where W, H and D correspond width, height and depth of the packet and ID is the ID of the packet and Description is the textual description.

        Parameters:
        e - the element to be loaded to the crane

      • unloadElement

        public StorageElement unloadElement()
        Unloads a StorageElement from the crane. For this, the crane has to be in its starting position. Also prints out some information about the unloading operation. The format for this is

        "(crane --%gt; packet_ID|size:WxHxD|DESCRIPTION)"

        where W, H and D correspond width, height and depth of the packet and ID is the ID of the packet and Description is the textual description.

        Returns:
        the element which has been loaded to the crane

      • retrieveElement

        public void retrieveElement()
        A StorageElement is retrieved from a StoragePlace of the harbor storage corresponding to the current position of the crane and is loaded to the crane. If there is no element to be retrieved, a CraneException is thrown. Also prints out some information about the retrieval operation - the format for this is

        (slot_NUMBER|xPXyPY|SWxSHxSD --> packet_ID|size:WxHxD|DESCRIPTION)

        where PX, PY is the position of the storage place, SW,SH,SD its width, height and depth, respectively. NUMBER is the number of the storage place and ID, W, H, D and DESCRIPTION are ID, width, height, depth and the textual description of the storage element, respectively.

      • storeElement

        public void storeElement()
        The StorageElement loaded to the crane is stored into the StoragePlace at the current position of the crane (and unloaded from the crane). If no element was loaded to the crane or the StoragePlace is already occupied, a StorageException is thrown. Also prints out some information about the retrieval operation - the format for this is

        (slot_NUMBER|xPXyPY|SWxSHxSD <-- packet_ID|size:WxHxD|DESCRIPTION)

        where PX, PY is the position of the storage place, SW,SH,SD its width, height and depth, respectively. NUMBER is the number of the storage place and ID, W, H, D and DESCRIPTION are ID, width, height, depth and the textual description of the storage element, respectively.

      • forward

        public void forward()
        Causes the crane to move forward (increasing) in horizontal (x-) direction. Does not stop until either backward() or stopX() is called. The position won't change anymore if the end of the high rack is reached -- in this case, the motor becomes stalled and isStalledX() will return true until the motor is stopped.

      • backward

        public void backward()
        Causes the crane to move backward (decreasing) in horizontal (x-) direction. Does not stop until either forward() or stopX() is called. The position won't change anymore if the end of the high rack is reached -- in this case, the motor becomes stalled and isStalledX() will return true until the motor is stopped.

      • up

        public void up()
        Causes the crane to move upward (increasing) in vertical (y-) direction. Does not stop until either down() or stopY() is called. The position won't change anymore when the end of the high rack is reached -- in this case, the motor becomes stalled and isStalledY() will return true until the motor is stopped.

      • down

        public void down()
        Causes the crane to move upward (decreasing) in vertical (y-) direction. Does not stop until either up() or stopY() is called. The position won't change anymore when the end of the high rack is reached -- in this case, the motor becomes stalled and isStalledY() will return true until the motor is stopped.

      • stopY

        public void stopY()
        Causes the crane to stop in vertical (y-) direction. The motor stops immediately upon call of this method.

      • stopX

        public void stopX()
        Causes the crane to stop in horizontal (x-) direction. The motor stops immediately upon call of this method.

      • isStalledX

        public boolean isStalledX()
        Ask if the crane's motor is stalled, that is, cannot move further along the x-direction (because it has driven over the borders of the high rack). When this happens, stopX() has to be called and the crane has to be moved into the right direction again.
        Returns:
        true, if the crane's motor is stalled false, if it is in a valid position and may move further

      • isStalledY

        public boolean isStalledY()

        Returns:
        true, if the crane's motor is stalled false, if it is in a valid position and may move further
